[[Image:Potbelly 6.jpg|thumb|right|350px| Takalik Abaj was continuously occupied for almost two thousand years.<ref>Popenoe de Hatch 2005, p.997.</ref> This photo shows the access stairway to Terrace 3, dating to the Late Preclassic.<ref>Garc<U+00ED>a 1997, p.176.</ref>]]
[[Image:TakalikAbajBallcourt.jpg|thumb|right|350px| Excavations of the [[Mesoamerican ballcourt|ballcourt]] at Takalik Abaj.]]
'''Tak'alik A'baj'''' is a [[pre-Columbian]] [[archaeology|archaeological]] site, formerly known as '''Abaj Takalik'''. It is one of several [[Mesoamerica]]n sites with both [[Olmec]] and [[Maya civilization|Maya]] features.  The site flourished in the [[Mesoamerican chronology|Pre-Classic]] and Classic eras, from the [[9th century BC]] through to at least the 10th century AD, and was an important commerce centre,<ref>Love 2007, p.297. Popenoe de Hatch 2005, pp.992, 994.</ref> trading with [[Kaminaljuyu]] and [[Chocol<U+00E1>]]. Investigations have revealed that it is one of the largest sites with sculptured monuments on the Pacific coastal plain.<ref>Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.236.</ref> Olmec-style sculptures include a possible colossal head, [[petroglyph]]s and others.<ref>Love 2007, p.288.</ref> The site has one of the greatest concentrations of Olmec-style sculpture outside of the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref>Love 2007, p.288.</ref>

Takalik Abaj is representative of the first blossoming of Maya culture that had occurred by about 400 BC.<ref>Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.33.</ref> Excavation is continuing at the site; the monumental architecture and long sequence of sculpture in a variety of styles suggest the site is of some importance.<ref>Adams 1996, p.81.</ref>

==Etymology==
The name means "Standing Stone" in the local [[K'iche' language|K'iche']] [[Maya language]], from ''tak<U+2019>alik'' (adj) meaning "standing" and ''ab<U+00E4>j'' (n) meaning "stone" or "rock".<ref>Christenson; Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26.</ref> Tak'alik A'baj was named ''Abaj Takalik'' by American archaeologist Susanna Miles,<ref>Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26. Note that Miles's first name is given variously as Suzanna (Kelly 1996, p.215.), Susanna (Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.239.) and Susan (Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26.)</ref> using Spanish word order. This is grammatically incorrect in K'iche';<ref>Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.26.</ref> the Guatemalan government has now officially corrected this to ''Tak'alik A'baj'''. The ancient name of the site is as yet unknown.

[[Image:Larger Southern Maya area v3.svg|left|400px|thumb|Takalik Abaj with relation to the Olmec heartland.]]

==Location==
The site lies in the southwest of [[Guatemala]], about 45km (28 miles) from the international border with [[Mexico]]<ref>Sharer 2000, p.467. Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.239.</ref> and 40km (25 miles) from the [[Pacific Ocean]].<ref>Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref>

Takalik Abaj is located in the north of the municipality of [[El Asintal]], in the extreme north of the [[Retalhuleu Department]] of Guatemala, some 120 miles (190 km) from [[Guatemala City]].<ref>Zetina Aldana and Escobar 1994, p.3. Kelly 1996, p.210. Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref>  The site lies among five coffee plantations in the lower foothills of the [[Sierra Madre de Chiapas|Sierra Madre]] mountains; the Santa Margarita, San Isidro Piedra Parada, Buenos Aires, San El<U+00ED>as and Dolores plantations.<ref>Zetina Aldana and Escobar 1994, p.3. Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref> Takalik Abaj sits upon a ridge running north-south, sloping in a southwards direction.<ref>Kelly 1996, p.210.</ref> This ridge is bordered on the west by the river Nim<U+00E1> and on the east by the river Ixchay<U+00E1>, both flowing down from the [[Guatemalan Highlands]].<ref>Zetina Aldana and Escobar 1994, p.3.</ref> The Ixchay<U+00E1> flows in a deep ravine but a suitable crossing point is located near to the site. The situation of Takalik Abaj at this crossing point was probably important in the founding of the city, since this channeled important trade routes through the site and controlled access to them.<ref>Popenoe de Hatch & Schieber de Lavarreda 2001, p.991.</ref>

Takalik Abaj sits at an altitude of approximately {{convert|600|m|ft}} above sea level in an area classed as [[subtropical moist forest]].<ref>Zetina Aldana and Escobar 1994, p.3. Rizzo de Robles 1991, p.32.</ref> The temperature normally varies between 21<U+00B0>C and 25<U+00B0>C (70<U+00B0>F and 77<U+00B0>F).<ref>Garc<U+00ED>a 1997, p.171.</ref> The area receives high annual rainfall, varying between {{convert|2136|and|4372|mm|in|0}}, with an average annual rainfall of {{convert|3284|mm|in|0}}.<ref>Zetina Aldana and Escobar 1994, p.18.</ref> Local vegetation includes the Pascua de Monta<U+00F1>a (''Pogonopus spesiosus''), Chichique (''Aspidosperma megalocarpum''), Tepecaulote (''Leuhea speciosa''), Caulote or West Indian Elm (''Guazuma ulminofolia''), Hormigo (''Platymiscium dimorphandrum''), [[Mexican Cedar]] (''Cedrela mexicana''), [[Breadnut]] (''Brosimum'' sp.), [[Tamarind]] (''Tamarindus indica'') and Papaturria (''[[Coccoloba montana]]'').<ref>Rizzo de Robles 1991, p.33.</ref>

A road passes the site, denominated 6W, running {{convert|30|km|mi}} from the town of [[Retalhuleu]] to [[Colomba|Colomba Costa Cuca]] in the department of [[Quetzaltenango (department)|Quetzaltenango]].<ref>Zetina Aldana and Escobar 1994, p.3. Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref>

Takalik Abaj is located at an approximate distance of 100km (62 miles) from the contemporary archaeological site of [[Monte Alto culture|Monte Alto]], 130km (81 miles) from [[Kaminaljuyu]] and 60km (37 miles) from [[Izapa]] in Mexico.<ref>Cassier & Ichon 1981, p.24.</ref>

[[Image:Formative Period southern Mesoamerica 2.svg|right|400px|thumb|Takalik Abaj and other Preclassic sites on the Pacific coast.]]

==Ethnicity==
The Middle Preclassic population of Takalik Abaj may have been speakers of Mixe-Zoque, the language associated with the Olmecs.<ref>Sharer & Traxler 2006, p.239. Popenoe de Hatch & Schieber de Lavarreda 2001, p.991.</ref> After the Maya intrusion into the site in the Late Preclassic the inhabitants presumably spoke a Maya language, although the exact one has not yet been identified.<ref>Popenoe de Hatch 2005, p.996.</ref> There are some hints from the indigenous chronicles that the inhabitants of the site may have been the Yoc Cancheb, a branch of the [[Mam people|Mam]] Maya.<ref>Popenoe de Hatch 2005, p.996.</ref>

==Economy and trade==
Takalik Abaj was one of a series of sites on the Pacific coastal plain that were important commercial, ceremonial and political centres. It is apparent that it prospered from the production of cacao and from the trade routes that crossed the region.<ref>Sharer 2000, p.455.</ref> At the time of the [[Spanish Conquest]] the area was still important for its production of [[cacao]].<ref>Coe 1999, p.64.</ref>

Study of [[Obsidian use in Mesoamerica|obsidian]] recovered at Takalik Abaj indicates that the majority originated from the [[El Chayal]] and [[San Mart<U+00ED>n Jilotepeque]] sources. Lesser quantities of obsidian originated from other sources such as [[Tajumulco]], [[Ixtepeque]] and [[Pachuca]].<ref>Crasborn 2005, p.696.</ref> The proportion of obsidian from different sources varied over time:

